Crewelwork on Oyster drapes and pillows from @jessica__close 
All of our fabrics are silk screen printed in London, the archival document we recreated here was a crewelwork fabric, hence the name. The actual color way of this one is called ‘Jungle Colors on Oyster’ because we took the colors from our Jungle print and used them and loved how it came out! 
But since that name gets a bit confusing and we almost never use the original color way - which was quite bright - we typically refer to this as simply Crewelwork on Oyster.

It is with great sadness that we announce the death of the unique and beautiful Gillian Newberry. She was inspirational and enriched our lives.
Gilly originally worked for the renowned decorator Geoffrey Bennison who had built up an archive of antique textile documents which he believed could be faithfully and sensitively reproduced for future generations. On his death in 1984 Gilly, with her husband Geoff, was able to continue his vision and opened Bennison Fabrics in 1985. Together the husband and wife along with Deb and Alex MacIntyre, both of whom also worked for Geoffrey Bennison, have produced some of the most beautiful fabrics in the world and will continue to do so with the team they built in England and America.
Gilly is survived by her husband Geoff, their children Jack and Holly, and 5 grandchildren.
Gilly had a wonderful sense of style, she was modest & caring and was loved beyond belief; she will be missed forever by us all.

Thank you everyone for your lovely words of support and encouragement. We are lucky to be able to see Gilly’s legacy through and continue the work of her life.

Roses Blue on Beige pretty much everywhere. This was one of Geoffrey Bennison’s original finds and a classic in its own right. The blue in the leaves is correct to the original document, printed in 1840. 
Back then the leaves were green, a process achieved by printing yellow over blue. The yellow was more volatile and  less fast, eventually fading away and leaving only the blue underneath. And that’s why we have blue leaves!
